    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-30T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-30T03:00:00-05:00" n="417"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d417">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW/10–3044: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-30T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 30, 1944—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 30—10:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4146. On October 28, immediately after the signing of the Bulgarian armistice
                    agreement (4138, October 28, 6 p.m.<note n="29" xml:id="d417fn29">Not
                        printed.</note>), I took the liberty of handing to Mr. Stainov<note n="30"
                        xml:id="d417fn30">Petko Stainov, Bulgarian Minister for Foreign
                        Affairs.</note> a letter, addressed to the Bulgarian armistice delegation,
                    stating that the United States Government <pb facs="0494" n="482"
                        xml:id="pg_482"/> expected the Bulgarian Government to break immediately all
                    relations with Japan. The wording of the letter was the same as that of the
                    letter addressed to the Rumanian armistice delegation on the same subject
                    (Embassy’s 3492, September 14, 7 p.m.<note n="31" xml:id="d417fn31">Vol. <hi
                            rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, section under Rumania entitled “Post-armistice
                        problems of occupation and control of Rumania …”</note>). The British
                        Ambassador,<note n="32" xml:id="d417fn32">Sir Archibald J. K. Clark
                        Kerr.</note> acting on instructions, was handing Mr. Stainov a similar
                    letter at that time, and I feared that any delay on our part in doing likewise
                    might invite interpretation.<note n="33" xml:id="d417fn33">Bulgaria severed
                        relations with Japan as of November 6.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to the Department as 4146; repeated to AmPolAd,<note n="34"
                        xml:id="d417fn34">American Political Adviser; Alexander C. Kirk was
                        Political Adviser on the staff of the Supreme Allied Commander,
                        Mediterranean (SACMED), Gen. Sir Henry Maitland Wilson.</note> Caserta, as
                    No. 7.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
